_normalized": false, "mention": "carbon tetrachloride", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999798059463501, "span": {"begin": 686, "end": 706}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30737"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "trichloromethyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992445707321167, "span": {"begin": 711, "end": 726}}, {"id": ["mesh:C029952"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "trichloromethyl peroxy", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997361898422241, "span": {"begin": 752, "end": 774}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002725"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "chloroform", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980373978614807, "span": {"begin": 790, "end": 800}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010705"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phosgene", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984351992607117, "span": {"begin": 805, "end": 813}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1571"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cyp2E1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9888398051261902, "span": {"begin": 852, "end": 858}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1571"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cyp2E1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9879032969474792, "span": {"begin": 934, "end": 940}}], "text": "Metabolism of xenobiotics by cytochrome P450 mono-oxygenases produces reactive metabolites. Under normal circumstances, these metabolites immediately become conjugated to molecules like glutathione or glucuronic acid, which facilitates their excretion. However, these metabolites can react with off-target cellular molecules, which in extreme cases (e.g., at toxic doses or following glutathione depletion during periods of oxidative stress) cause damage that results in hepatotoxicity. Typically, the unmetabolised Cyp2E1 substrates are inert, whereas their metabolites are highly cytotoxic; e.g., furan and its metabolite cis-2-butene-1,4-dial (BDA); ethanol (EtOH) and acetaldehyde; carbon tetrachloride and trichloromethyl radical (which forms the trichloromethyl peroxy radical); and, chloroform and phosgene. Lipid peroxidation in the context of Cyp2E1 has been reviewed (Caro and Cederbaum 2004). Moreover, chronic exposure to Cyp2E1 agonists depletes of conjugating enzymes and &nbsp;diminishes capacity to deal with reactive metabolites in the cell.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:02:18 +0000 2026"}